Remove the old container:
  docker compose -f docker-* down fms-traffic-management-service

Remove existing images (both latest + stable)
  docker rmi -f fms-traffic-management-service:latest fms-traffic-management-service:stable

Confirm:
  docker images | grep fms-traffic-management-service

Rebuild just that one service:
  docker compose -f docker-compose.prod.yml build traffic-management-service

If you want it to automatically recreate the container:
  docker compose up -d --build fms-traffic-management-service

Check that it built correctly:
  docker images | grep fms-traffic-management-service

Tag it as stable (Once confirmed, tag the new image as stable):
  docker tag fms-traffic-management-service:latest fms-traffic-management-service:stable

Save it:
  docker save -o /home/govind/FMS-backups/fms-traffic-management-service_stable.tar fms-traffic-management-service:stable && gzip /home/govind/FMS-backups/fms-traffic-management-service_stable.tar


load it on server (On another machine, restore it like this):
  gzip -d fms-traffic-management-service_stable.tar.gz
  docker load -i fms-traffic-management-service_stable.tar
